1. FlexWord Sound Philosophy (Design Doc)
Core Principle
Silent-first. Expressive by choice. Accessible by design.
FlexWord is designed to be comfortably playable:
in public
at work
late at night
without headphones
Sound is never required to play or succeed.
Philosophy Pillars
1. Silent by Default
All sound effects are OFF by default
No surprise audio
No background music
This matches player expectations set by Wordle and other daily word games.
2. Sound = Confirmation, Not Stimulation
Sound is used only to:
confirm actions
signal outcomes
reinforce success
Sound is never used to punish, rush, or distract.
3. Accessibility Is a First-Class Use Case
Sound effects are designed to:
supplement color feedback
support low-vision and colorblind players
work alongside screen readers
Audio is descriptive, not decorative.
4. Player Control Above All
Players can:
enable/disable sound at any time
control sound effects independently of system volume
play the entire game without audio
No gameplay advantage is tied to sound.
Non-Goals (Explicit)
FlexWord does not aim to:
create a musical identity
provide ambient audio
gamify sound
compete for attention via audio
Quiet confidence > noise.
2. Sound Events Specification (Implementation-Ready)
Below is a minimal, intentional sound event list.
If an event is not listed here, it should not make sound.
Global Rules
All sounds:
< 300ms
low-volume
soft attack / fast decay
No overlapping sounds
Respect system mute
Core Gameplay Events
